President Biden’s budget proposal calls for an increase in capital gains tax up to 44.6%!  This would be the highest capital gains tax the US has ever seen.

There’s more: it also calls for a 25% tax on unrealized capital gains.

It’s only for households worth at least $100 million. But what exactly does that mean? It means that a large portion of entrepreneurs and early employees of successful companies could go bankrupt. If you don’t know, when you don’t pay your debt to a creditor, that money gets sent to “collections”.

This means that the creditor has given up hope on you ever repaying back your debt.

So, they sell the right to your debt to a debt collection agency for a small percentage of the original amount.

This frees your original creditor of having to deal with you, while also recouping a small amount of the loss, and also gives tax benefits to your creditor.

This also gives the collection agency the opportunity to get you to pay them far more than what they paid for your debt.

tweet_1800483979818160423.user_comment:
For an example, let’s say you owe Chase Bank $2500. After they’ve lost hope that you will pay them back, they will sell your $2500 debt to a collections agency for pennies on the dollar.

This debt collection agency has bought your $2500 debt for $100, and then calls and mails you repeatedly trying to get you to pay back the full $2500, giving them a profit of $2400.

In reality, these collection agencies are trying as hard possible to get you to pay ANYTHING. They know you’re a risk and likely won’t pay it, that’s why the debt was sold so cheaply.

Huge news today everyone! 📰🌱

The @POTUS  administration plans to ease federal restrictions on cannabis by moving it from Schedule I to Schedule III of the Controlled Substances Act.

The DEA supports the opinion by the Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) for this change. Attorney General Merrick Garland will submit the proposal to the White House Office of Management and Budget.

This reclassification recognizes the potential medical benefits of marijuana, allowing for more comprehensive research.

Why is this important you ask?

Medical Research: Moving cannabis to Schedule III facilitates more research into its medical uses, potentially leading to new treatments and therapies.

Legal Implications: Reclassification could ease some of the legal constraints, reducing penalties associated with marijuana-related offenses.

Economic Impact: This change might boost the cannabis industry by easing banking, insurance, and taxation challenges that businesses currently face.

Some of the broader effects that will be interesting to see...

Individuals: Patients might gain better access to medical marijuana with more doctors willing to prescribe it and more pharmacies stocking it.

Law Enforcement: Shifts focus away from penalizing possession, allowing more resources for combating more severe crimes.

Medical Community: Opens new avenues for researchers to explore marijuana's benefits and risks, potentially leading to broader acceptance and use in medical treatment.

This is huge, and is a significant shift in drug policy, reflecting changing attitudes towards marijuana.

@JoeBiden #legalizeit #legalizeweed #DEA
